{"amendments":[{"body":"In `src/adapters/process_backend.rs:1288-1321`, make `extract_codex_usage_from_stdout` skip lines where `usage` is missing, null, non-object, or contains none of the recognized token fields. The current reverse scan stops on any `usage` key and returns all-`None` counts, so a trailing event like `{\"usage\":null}` or `{\"usage\":{}}` will discard a valid earlier `turn.completed` usage record. Add a regression test for that shape.","rationale":"This silently drops Codex token/cache metrics on mixed NDJSON streams, which is exactly the data this change is supposed to restore."},{"body":"Move or duplicate the new `tracing::info!` in `src/contexts/agent_execution/service.rs:240-277` so it fires immediately after metadata finalization, before `persist_raw_output`, `extract_structured_payload`, and contract validation. As written, any failure in those later steps returns before the log call, so malformed or contract-invalid invocations still emit no token/cache trace event.","rationale":"The bead asks for per-invocation token/cache observability. Right now the implementation only logs on the fully successful path, leaving the highest-value failure cases invisible."}],"summary":"Reviewed the task diff end-to-end and ran `cargo test --quiet` plus `cargo clippy --quiet -- -D warnings`. I found two robustness gaps: Codex NDJSON usage extraction can stop on null/empty `usage` entries and lose real token data, and the new invocation tracing only runs after several fallible post-processing steps, so failed invocations still miss the promised token/cache event."}